# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: blackadder-clipper
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:blackadder-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Captain **Alfred Bulltop Stormalong** was an American folk hero and the subject of numerous nautical-themed tall tales originating in Massachusetts.
[src:blackadder-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Stormalong was said to be a sailor and a giant, some 30 feet (9.1 m) tall; he was the master of a huge clipper ship known in various sources as either the *Courser* or the *Tuscarora*, a ship purportedly so tall that it had hinged masts to avoid catching on the Moon.
[src:blackadder-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] The name of Stormalong first appeared in a cycle of sea shanties that Stan Hugill, in his *Sea Shanties of the Seven Seas*, traces back to African-American folk songs of the 1830s and '40s.
[src:blackadder-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Bearing names like "Mister Stormalong", "Way Stormalong John", and "Yankee John, Stormalong", these sailors' work songs generally featured praise for a deceased seaman and for his benevolent son.
[src:blackadder-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] The tall tales about Stormalong first appeared in the 1911 book *Here's Audacity!* by Frank Shay.
[src:blackadder-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] More tales appeared in the 1933 pamphlet *Old Stormalong Yarns* by C.E.
[src:blackadder-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] New England was where he was beached as a baby, already three fathoms (18 ft) tall.
[src:blackadder-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] According to one telling, he outgrew Cape Cod and moved to Boston, where he signed aboard the first ship that would take him at the age of twelve.
[src:blackadder-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] He had a lifelong rivalry with a Kraken, a huge sea monster from Norse myth; in fact, the Kraken escaped from him in their first encounter, causing a dejected Stormalong to abandon the sea life for life as a farmer somewhere in the Midwest.
[src:blackadder-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Some sources say he had a ship so large that a stable of Arabian horses were aboard for his crew to get from one end of the ship to the other.
[src:blackadder-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Among other things, the ship Alfred was best said to have drilled the course of the Panama Canal by slamming into the Panamanian coast, and to have gotten stuck in the English Channel, which required the crew to grease the ship's hull with soap.
[src:blackadder-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] The soap combined with the scraping of the hull against the Gray Cliffs of Dover turned them bright white.
[src:blackadder-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] As Stormalong grew older, he eventually encountered the Kraken again, this time successfully drawing the beast into a whirlpool from which it never escaped.
[src:blackadder-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] The aged Stormalong won the race by several miles, but the stress of handling the wheel through the difficult Atlantic crossing killed him.
[src:blackadder-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Stormalong was buried at sea, and Davy Jones himself opened his famous locker to accept Stormalong's body.
[src:blackadder-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Another ending to his life is as follows: While Stormalong was on his Caribbean adventures, he passed by Florida, seeing that there was a tremendous hurricane that tore through his ship.
[src:blackadder-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Ships sailing nearby were being tossed around by the heavy waves.
[src:blackadder-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Stormalong went overboard and piled as many boats as he could onto his ship.
[src:blackadder-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] When the storm finally wound down, the sailors were dropped back off at Florida.
[src:blackadder-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] After that, he went back on board, unfurling the sails of his ship, seeing if they could be repaired.
[src:blackadder-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] A great wind, the last blow of the hurricane, hit the sails, lifting Stormalong and his ship into the sky.
[src:blackadder-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] A third ending to his life takes advantage of the inference that, being a giant, Alfred Bulltop Stormalong was an enormous eater.
[src:blackadder-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] It describes a time when his hunger was greater than usual and led him to eat so much food (one variant cites a breakfast of six sharks; it is not definitely known what other variants exist) that he suffered terminal indigestion, causing his magnificent appetite to finish him.
[src:blackadder-clipper/ambassador-clipper] William Walker built *Ambassador* at Lavender Dry Dock in London.
[src:blackadder-clipper/ambassador-clipper] Though considered a fast ship, *Ambassador* was said to be "very cranky and overmasted".
[src:blackadder-clipper/ambassador-clipper] Her first passage to the UK from Fuzhou came during the Tea Race of 1870 under Captain Duggan and took 115 days, a mediocre performance; that same year the fastest tea passage, also from Fuzhou, was made by the clipper *Lahloo* in just 98 days.
[src:blackadder-clipper/ambassador-clipper] *Ambassador*'s fastest passage between China and England was 108 days, in 1872.
[src:blackadder-clipper/ambassador-clipper] The wreck is now reduced to a skeletal frame.
[src:blackadder-clipper/amboy-schooner-barge] The ***Amboy*** was a wooden schooner barge that sank along with her towing steamer, the *George Spencer* on Lake Superior off the coast of Schroeder, Cook County, Minnesota in the United States.
[src:blackadder-clipper/amboy-schooner-barge] In 1994 the remains of the *Amboy* were added to the National Register of Historic Places.
[src:blackadder-clipper/amboy-schooner-barge] The *Amboy* (Official number 95276) was a wooden schooner barge that was constructed specifically for the Minnesota's iron ore trade.
[src:blackadder-clipper/amboy-schooner-barge] She was built in 1874 by Quayle & Murphy of Cleveland, Ohio.
[src:blackadder-clipper/amboy-schooner-barge] She had a gross tonnage of 893 tons, and a net tonnage of 849 tons.
[src:blackadder-clipper/amboy-schooner-barge] She could carry approximately 1,500 tons of cargo.
[src:blackadder-clipper/amboy-schooner-barge] In July 1891 the *Helena* sank in a collision in the Little Mud Lake, St.
[src:blackadder-clipper/amboy-schooner-barge] On August 26, 1892, the *Amboy* arrived in Cleveland, Ohio, full of water.
[src:blackadder-clipper/amboy-schooner-barge] She was traveling from Escanaba, Michigan, when she was caught in a storm.
[src:blackadder-clipper/amboy-schooner-barge] Eventually the amount of water pouring into her hull became too much for the pumps to empty.
[src:blackadder-clipper/amboy-schooner-barge] She was eventually saved by the tugboats *Gregory* and *Blazier*; they towed the *Amboy* to Cleveland.
[src:blackadder-clipper/amboy-schooner-barge] On October 14, 1893, the *Amboy* ran aground at the foot of Georgia Street in Buffalo, New York.
[src:blackadder-clipper/amboy-schooner-barge] She was in tow of the steamer *Helena* but broke away in the strong gale.
[src:blackadder-clipper/amboy-schooner-barge] The *Helena* left the *Amboy* to be freed by tugboats.
[src:blackadder-clipper/amboy-schooner-barge] Eventually the tug *Cascade* came to her assistance and after about half an hours work she was freed.
[src:blackadder-clipper/amboy-schooner-barge] On September 5, 1898, at around 10:00A.M. the *Amboy* ran aground in the Niagara River near the Germania Park.
[src:blackadder-clipper/amboy-schooner-barge] She was under tow of the tug *James Byers*; she was bound from Tonawanda, New York with a cargo of iron ore in her cargo hold.
[src:blackadder-clipper/amboy-schooner-barge] Low water levels caused her keel to hit bottom and run aground.
[src:blackadder-clipper/amboy-schooner-barge] Eventually the tugs *Cascade*, *Hibbard* and *Conneaut* arrived to try to free her but also failed.
[src:blackadder-clipper/amboy-schooner-barge] A lighter was also sent to try to rescue her by removing part of her cargo.
[src:blackadder-clipper/amboy-schooner-barge] On the day of November 28, 1905 the *Amboy* and the wooden bulk freighter *George Spencer* were bound from Buffalo, New York for Duluth, Minnesota with a cargo of coal when they were struck by the full force of the Mataafa Storm.
[src:blackadder-clipper/amboy-schooner-barge] After the storm blew itself out it was discovered that 18 ships were wrecked or stranded; and one, the steamer *Ira H.
[src:blackadder-clipper/amboy-schooner-barge] The crew of the *Spencer* cut the line between her and the *Amboy* in an attempt to save both of the ships.
[src:blackadder-clipper/amboy-schooner-barge] The crew of the ships escaped the vessels with a breeches' buoy which was rigged up by some nearby fishermen.
[src:blackadder-clipper/amboy-schooner-barge] The remains of the *Amboy* lie not too far from the wreck of the *Spencer*.
[src:blackadder-clipper/amboy-schooner-barge] The remains of the *Amboy'*s 74-foot (23 m) keelson is encased in sand and cobbles.
[src:blackadder-clipper/amboy-schooner-barge] The section of her keelson which is parallel to the beach has been eroded by the waves, it consists of side-by-side white oak timbers.
[src:blackadder-clipper/amboy-schooner-barge] It is two timbers high and secured with hundreds of iron bolts that are 1.25 and .875 inches in diameter.
[src:blackadder-clipper/amboy-schooner-barge] Near the southern end of the timbers there is an upright timber which is believed to be part of her centreboard.
[src:blackadder-clipper/amboy-schooner-barge] These remains can easily be viewed with satellite imagery, such as Google Earth.
[src:blackadder-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] The ***Andrew Jackson*** was a 1,679-registered-ton medium clipper built by the firm of Irons & Grinnell in Mystic, Connecticut in 1855.
[src:blackadder-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] The vessel was designed for the shipping firm of J.H.
[src:blackadder-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] Brower & Co. to carry cargo intended for sale to participants in the California Gold Rush.
[src:blackadder-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] The ship was 220 feet (67 m) in length, had a beam of 41 ft., 2 in., and a draft 22 ft., 3 in.
[src:blackadder-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] The vessel was described as "a very handsome, well-designed ship.
[src:blackadder-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] This was one of only three 89-day runs performed by square-rigged ships driving from New York City to California.
[src:blackadder-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] The other two runs were both posted by *Flying Cloud*.
[src:blackadder-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] *Flying Cloud*'s fastest New York-to-California run had taken 89 days and 8 hours; *Andrew Jackson*'s run was, by four hours, widely acclaimed in the newspapers as the fastest in history.
[src:blackadder-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] Some clipper ship authorities, including Howe and Matthews, assert that *Andrew Jackson* did not actually set the record described above.
[src:blackadder-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] They concede, however, that this medium clipper, perhaps not naturally as fast as *Flying Cloud*, achieved a remarkable passage as the result of a combination of hard driving by the captain and favorable winds.
[src:blackadder-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] However, after careful scrutiny of the logbooks, one author, Carl C.
[src:blackadder-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] Cutler, concludes that a case can be made for either *Flying Cloud* or *Andrew Jackson* holding the record.
[src:blackadder-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] Some will consider the passage from pilot-to-pilot as the appropriate indicator of fastest sailing performance around Cape Horn.
[src:blackadder-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] *Flying Cloud* holds the record time for a passage anchor-to-anchor from New York to San Francisco, of 89 days 8 hours, while *Andrew Jackson'*s completed passage anchor-to-anchor may have been as long as 89 days 20 hours.
[src:blackadder-clipper/anglona-clipper] The schooner ***Anglona*** was the first American opium clipper.
[src:blackadder-clipper/anglona-clipper] She sailed in the Chinese coastal trade in the 1840s, and had a famous race with the schooner *Ariel* around Lintin Island.
[src:blackadder-clipper/anglona-clipper] Forbes was interested in fast schooners for clipper and coastal service in China.
[src:blackadder-clipper/anglona-clipper] The first clipper which Forbes sent to China, the *Rose*, foundered in the July typhoon of 1841.
[src:blackadder-clipper/anglona-clipper] Forbes purchased *Anglona* at Brown & Bell's New York yard for Russell & Co. for use as a despatch boat between Hong Kong, Macao, and Whampoa.
[src:blackadder-clipper/anglona-clipper] Other American pilot boat models sent to China in the 1840s included the *Zephyr* and the *Spec*, also built on the New York model.
[src:blackadder-clipper/anglona-clipper] Shortly after Shanghai opened to foreign trade, three Boston pilot boats were sent: the 90 ton *Golden Gate*, the 90 ton *Siren*, and the 75 ton *Daniel Webster*, which served as pilot boats in the Yangtze River.
[src:blackadder-clipper/anglona-clipper] Within two weeks of purchase, *Anglona* sailed for China under Captain Turner.
[src:blackadder-clipper/anglona-clipper] She arrived at Cape Horn in 61 days, and Java Head in 95 days.
[src:blackadder-clipper/anglona-clipper] Russell & Co put *Anglona* in service on the Canton River until the new treaty ports opened, at which time she was put in the coastal trade.
[src:blackadder-clipper/anglona-clipper] Captain Turner did not serve long, as he was knocked overboard by the mainboom during a sudden jibe, and drowned.
[src:blackadder-clipper/anglona-clipper] In 1843, *Anglona* was under command of Capt.
[src:blackadder-clipper/anglona-clipper] Adamson; in 1844 she was under Captain Macfarlane.
[src:blackadder-clipper/anglona-clipper] On September 20, 1841, *Anglona* left Hong Kong with a 108-ton cargo of rice from Macao bound for the East Coast; on Dec.
[src:blackadder-clipper/anglona-clipper] 2, she left Hong Kong with a 108-ton cargo from Macao of opium or specie bound for Namoa.
[src:blackadder-clipper/anglona-clipper] Lee, the designer of the *Rose*, wanted to know why Forbes hadn't come to him for a clipper schooner instead, and got Forbes to agree to taking a half interest in one of his schooners if it could beat the *Anglona*.
[src:blackadder-clipper/anglona-clipper] The *Ariel*, a new 92-ton schooner built by Sprague & James at Medford, MA was taken out for a trial in 1841 out of Lewis Wharf in Boston Harbor, against the 30 ton schooner-yacht *Breeze*, which had been built for Forbes by Daniel C.
[src:blackadder-clipper/anglona-clipper] The wind had freshened and was blowing in hard puffs.
[src:blackadder-clipper/anglona-clipper] He had suggested taking in a second reef, but his companions assured him the wind would slacken as they approached the harbor.
[src:blackadder-clipper/anglona-clipper] In stays off Sound Point Beacon, the Ariel laid down before she could get way on for a tack towards Long Island, and sank in seven fathoms of water.
[src:blackadder-clipper/anglona-clipper] When *Ariel* was refloated, Lee agreed to reduce the rig, and cut down the masts as per Forbes’ suggestion.
[src:blackadder-clipper/anglona-clipper] *Ariel* was then sent to China under Capt.
[src:blackadder-clipper/anglona-clipper] Poor, making an 80-day passage to Anjer.
[src:blackadder-clipper/anglona-clipper] The race between *Ariel* and *Anglona* was about 40 mi., from Macao Roads around Lintin and back, for stakes of $1,000 and Forbes’ agreement to take half-interest in *Ariel* if she won.
[src:blackadder-clipper/anglona-clipper] *Anglona* was much stronger sailing to windward, due to the shallow draft of *Ariel,* and took the lead until rounding the island.
[src:blackadder-clipper/anglona-clipper] At that point, *Ariel* set a large flying square sail and topsail.
[src:blackadder-clipper/anglona-clipper] *Anglona* had no ballooning sails for running downwind, and was beaten by 17 minutes.
[src:blackadder-clipper/anjou-ship] On 7 February, a signpost to the boat shed was discovered and the castaways went to Camp Cove.
[src:blackadder-clipper/anjou-ship] The crew took shelter in the boat shed and hunted seals, birds and shellfish for food.
[src:blackadder-clipper/anjou-ship] It wasn't until the tenth day that they discovered the castaway depot and a notice that the depot received regular visits from the New Zealand Government steam ships.
[src:blackadder-clipper/anjou-ship] The crew built additional huts of scrub and tussock and waited for rescue.
[src:blackadder-clipper/anjou-ship] Fearing that supplies of food would run short they continued to supplement their diet with local wildlife and also sought out the other depot on the Islands.
[src:blackadder-clipper/anjou-ship] On 7 May, Captain John Bollons anchored *Hinemoa* in Camp Cove and rescued the castaways.
[src:blackadder-clipper/anjou-ship] He restocked the castaway depots and returned to New Zealand with the crew of *Anjou* via Campbell Island as was his normal route.
[src:blackadder-clipper/anjou-ship] Unlike other shipwrecks on the Auckland Islands the survivors had only a short stay of a little over three months before being rescued.
[src:blackadder-clipper/anjou-ship] Other castaways, such as those from *Grafton*, *General Grant*, and *Dundonald*, had significantly longer stays and suffered much hardship and loss of life.
[src:blackadder-clipper/anjou-ship] The exact location of the wreck of *Anjou* was found as a result of repeated attempts to find the wreck of *General Grant* during the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:blackadder-clipper/anjou-ship] *General Grant* is rumoured to have been carrying a significant quantity of gold from the Australian gold fields when it was wrecked on the island in 1864.
[src:blackadder-clipper/anjou-ship] The exact location of the wreck of *General Grant* has never been confirmed although there have been numerous searches.
[src:blackadder-clipper/anjou-ship] In 1975, the search team led by John Gratton found the wreck of *Anjou* but although the divers recovered several artifacts none could confirm the wreck's identity.
[src:blackadder-clipper/anjou-ship] Gratton and his team returned to the site in 1976 and another team visited in 1977 but it was not until 1986 when a syndicate of divers were able to prove that the site was the wreck of *Anjou*.
[src:blackadder-clipper/anjou-ship] A number of artifacts from the wreck are in the collection of the Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa.
[src:blackadder-clipper/antelope-of-boston] The hull was black, the inside dark buff with blue waterways.
[src:blackadder-clipper/antelope-of-boston] In 1853, *Antelope* arrived in San Francisco from New York under Captain Snow on August 31 after a passage of 128 days, returning to New York via Callao in 178 days.
[src:blackadder-clipper/antelope-of-boston] After one more round trip to the West Coast of South America *Antelope* went into the China trade.
[src:blackadder-clipper/antelope-of-boston] In July 1858, *Antelope* departed Bangkok for China under Captain Clarke.
[src:blackadder-clipper/antelope-of-boston] On August 6, she struck on Discovery Shoal, Paracels Reef, which was not visible due to a high, ending her sailing career after six years and nine months.
[src:blackadder-clipper/antelope-of-boston] Captain Clarke, four passengers, and 13 seamen abandoned ship, and set out in one of the ship's boats.
[src:blackadder-clipper/antelope-of-boston] A second boat, which became separated during the night, carried the mate, one seaman, and ten Chinese passengers.
[src:blackadder-clipper/antelope-of-boston] Four days later, a Chinese fishing junk came into view.
[src:blackadder-clipper/antelope-of-boston] Clarke offered the fishermen $20 for a tow to a place where water could be had.
[src:blackadder-clipper/antelope-of-boston] Once the *Antelope* party was taken in tow, it became evident that the fishermen were not trustworthy.
[src:blackadder-clipper/antelope-of-boston] Fearing piracy, the shipwrecked party cut the tow rope and attempted an escape.
[src:blackadder-clipper/antelope-of-boston] The fishermen pursued the boat, attacked it with stones, and finally set two fishermen to stand guard with spears while the others robbed the *Antelope* party.
[src:blackadder-clipper/antelope-of-boston] In the midst of the confusion, two of the *Antelope* sailors took advantage of the distraction and boarded the fishing junk, dispatching its crew.
[src:blackadder-clipper/antelope-of-boston] Captain Clarke also attempted to board the junk, but fell in the water and had to be rescued.
[src:blackadder-clipper/antelope-of-boston] The shipwrecked *Antelope* party then took command of the junk, and arrived in Hong Kong on August 14.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] Jock Willis & Sons operated a shipping line which specialised in fast sailing cargo ships, including tea clippers trading tea from China.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] These were 'state of the art' ships designed to take part in what had become a race to be the fastest ship home with the new season tea.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] The opening of the Suez Canal in 1869 together with steady improvements in steam engineering meant that sailing ships were slowly being replaced by steam ships, which could operate on guaranteed timetables and make use of the shorter route through the canal, which was unsuitable for sailing ships.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] However, steamers had the disadvantage of having to purchase coal for the journey and to carry coal, reducing the space available for cargo.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] A number of ship owners therefore still believed there was a place for good sailing ships, and these continued in profitable service for many years.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] In 1869 Jock Willis, junior (son of Jock Willis, senior, founder of the company) had commissioned another clipper, *Cutty Sark*, which was a composite design (timber hull on iron frame).
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] He now commissioned two further ships, but this time with iron hulls.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] As was the case with *Cutty Sark*, the shape of the hull for the ships was based upon another ship belonging to Willis, *The Tweed* (previously named *Punjaub*).
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] This was a former sail/paddle steamer frigate built in Bombay for the East India Company, later sold when the East India company navy was merged into the Royal Navy.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] Willis removed the engines and paddle wheels and found he had an exceptionally good sailing ship.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] Ritherdon and Thompson, the surveyors to the East India Council, were commissioned to prepare drawings for the new ships based upon *The Tweed*.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] Although similar below the water and of very similar size, the two ships looked somewhat different from *Cutty Sark*.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] Maudsley and Co. were contracted to construct the ship, although they were an engineering company relatively inexperienced with whole ship design.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] This was not dissimilar to Willis' choice in builders for *Cutty Sark* which was also a new and inexperienced company, which in that instance became bankrupt before *Cutty Sark* was completed.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] The contract was signed in June 1869 and the ship launched March 1870, to the highest Lloyds standards and using the best materials.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] Cargo was starting to be loaded on board the ship even before installation of the masts had been completed.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] Masts on such a ship are sectional and are installed in overlapping pieces with stays (lines) running up from the deck to fixing points on each section to hold the masts steady.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] It was noticed that the stays were slack, so they were re-tightened, only for them to be found slack again the following day.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] On further examination it was discovered that the metal cradles which supported the topmasts had been incorrectly manufactured, and had simply bent out of shape once tension had been applied on the stays.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] Rather than remove the masts to repair the damage, additional strengthening was added to hold together the cradles and provide new fixing points.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] However, the bent ironwork could not be repaired with the masts in place.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] During the journey it became clear that repairs had been inadequate.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] Chains were added to the mainmast to help support its topmast, and it was noticed that rivets holding the collar around the mainmast were becoming loose.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] The ship's carpenter proposed drilling through the mast and inserting a winch handle to ensure the collar stayed in place, but the captain refused.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] Only the skysail yards were taken down to reduce loading on the masts.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] At about midnight, with the wind slackening and changing direction and approaching the Roaring Forties, the captain decided to trim the ship and ordered a change in helm.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] Despite care by the helmsman to carry out the turn as slowly as possible so as to minimise the stress on the masts as the pressure from the winds changed, the inevitable rolling of the ship as it ceased to be pushed along while turning caused the collar to break away and the lower rigging with it.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] The continuing rolling meant the masts leaned one way and then the other, each time becoming looser.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] The iron mainmast buckled below the level of the deck, tearing the deck as it did, ending leaning to port at 45 degrees.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] Shortly the remaining supports gave way and with an extra large roll, the mast tore further through the deck and fell overboard.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] Braces to the mizzen mast from the main had been torn away, and it too started to rock loose.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] Despite attempts to get a line on it, while also trying to clear lines still attached to the sinking mainmast, this mast too fell, this time backwards across the stern of the ship, just missing the wheel.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] Crew worked to get the mizzen free and overboard, as it rolled dangerously about on the deck.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] The sole remaining mast was now unsupported because its braces from the mainmast had also gone, but in this case, the crew managed to get lines tightened to hold it in place.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] Both fore topsail yards had been snapped as the falling main mast pulled on them, and the other yards were pulled out of place.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] The following morning two men went aloft on the still swaying foremast to try to clear the broken rigging and yards.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] The royal yard came loose and fell, bringing with it part of the fore topgallant mast.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] Over the next three days the crew managed to salvage enough yards to have three sails on the foremast plus stunsails and set course for Simon's Bay.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] Mungo* saw the state of *Blackadder* and tried to come to assist, but was unable to catch up.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] Approaching False Bay to anchor, the ship fouled a wreck and before repairs were completed was in collision with two other vessels.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] Replacement masts and yards were sent out from Britain and the ship eventually proceeded to Shanghai.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] On the way she collided with a French mail steamer, and after further repairs lost her jibboon in yet another collision at Penang.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] She returned to London, arriving 17 November 1871 without further notable incident.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] The ship's insurers refused to pay out on claims for the damage, on the grounds the ship had been unseaworthy when it set out, and eighteen months of litigation against the builders ensued.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] The ship's captain was dismissed and replaced with Captain Moore.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] The following season's journey to China was relatively uneventful, only involving the loss of the mizzen topgallant mast in a collision.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] Moore was moved to command *Cutty Sark* and replaced with Sam Bissett, who had been mate on the maiden voyage.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] Carrying coal from Sydney to Shanghai she was caught in a typhoon, which caused the ship to heel over so much that the main and mizzen masts had to be cut away once more to right her.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] The cargo had shifted and had to be moved before the ship could be properly righted, but she limped on to Shanghai where new masts were fitted and she proceeded to Iloio and loaded a cargo for Boston.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] In the China sea the ship hit an uncharted reef and stuck fast, despite throwing the cargo overboard.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] The ship was abandoned and the crew taken off by *Albyn's isle*, which had come to their assistance.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] A squall sprang up, which now blew the ship clear of the reef and after a chase of some hours, the crew managed to reboard the ship and take control of their vessel again.
[src:blackadder-clipper/blackadder-clipper] For the fourth season she was commanded by Captain White.
